ce:section.ce:para:
The analytical performance of the ECL biosensor is evaluated by detection of HIV DNA and HPV-16 DNA at various concentrations. Fig. 4
                        A shows the ECL intensity increases gradually with the increase of HIV DNA concentration from 100 fM to 1 μM. A good correlation of ΔECL (ECL change of signal between the different concentration of target and without target) versus the logarithm of HIV DNA concentration is obtained in the investigated concentration range (Fig. 4B). The linear regression equation is ΔECL = 15871.17 + 1132.48 lgC (R2 = 0.9970). The limit of detection (LOD) is 30 fM (calculated by S/N = 3). As presented in Fig. 4C, the ECL intensity decreases gradually with increasing concentrations of HPV-16 DNA in the range from 1 pM to 100 nM. A good correlation of ΔECL versus the logarithm of HPV-16 DNA concentration is obtained in the investigated concentration range (Fig. 4D). The linear equation is ΔECL = 17774.5 + 1421.26 lgC (R2 = 0.9930) with the LOD of 0.32 pM. The different LOD of HIV and HPV-16 DNA may be due to the different detection principles: HIV detection uses DNA hybridization to form a sandwich DNA structure, while HPV detection is based on the trans-cleavage ability of CRISPR/Cas 12a, which is highly rely on the digestion activity of Cas12a protein. In comparison with some previous reported methods (Table 1
                        ), our signal-switchable ECL biosensor shows comparable detection limits for both HIV and HPV-16 DNAs.
